│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The assertion in LoopVectorizationPlanner::computeBestVF() fires because the  │
│ VF chosen by the new VPlan-based cost model (BestFactor.Width) disagrees with │
│ the VF chosen by the legacy cost model (LegacyVF.Width), and the fallback     │
│ check planContainsAdditionalSimplifications() returns false, meaning there    │
│ are no extra simplifications in the selected VPlan to justify the difference. │
│ In the provided reproducer, the loop is extremely simple and likely not       │
│ profitable to vectorize. The legacy model picks a vector VF while the         │
│ VPlan-based model picks scalar (or vice versa), causing the assertion.        │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The crash happens immediately inside computeBestVF(), before any IR           │
│ transformation is performed. This confirms the failure is confined to the     │
│ cost-model selection logic. The debug-only output was empty because the pass  │
│ aborts during VF selection. The assertion condition:                          │
│   (BestFactor.Width == LegacyVF.Width ||                                      │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications(...))                                   │
│ indicates widths differ and planContainsAdditionalSimplifications returned    │
│ false. This means the discrepancy is purely due to differing cost             │
│ computations, not structural simplifications.                                 │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ Inside computeBestVF(), scalar cost is computed using:                        │
│   InstructionCost ScalarCost = CM.expectedCost(ScalarVF);                     │
│ while vector VFs use the new unified VPlan-based cost path:                   │
│   InstructionCost Cost = cost(*P, VF);                                        │
│ This mixes two different cost modeling strategies: scalar uses only the       │
│ legacy cost model; vector uses the hybrid precomputeCosts + Plan.cost. In     │
│ contrast, selectVectorizationFactor() (legacy verifier path) uses             │
│ CM.expectedCost() uniformly for all VFs. Because the new path compares vector │
│ costs (VPlan-based) against a scalar cost (legacy-only), profitability        │
│ decisions can diverge from those of the all-legacy path even in the absence   │
│ of additional simplifications. For very small loops (like the reproducer with │
│ trivially constant computations) the mismatch is more pronounced: the scalar  │
│ cost may appear relatively worse or better compared to a differently scaled   │
│ vector cost, leading to different VF choices and triggering the assertion     │
│ that assumes consistency unless simplifications exist. The comment above this │
│ code even has a TODO acknowledging scalar cost should also use the            │
│ VPlan-based cost model.                                                       │
│ Thus the root cause is the inconsistent costing method for scalar VF=1 versus │
│ vector VFs in computeBestVF(), violating the assumption behind the assertion. │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ Edit lines 7336-7338 in llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp.      │
│ Replace the legacy-only scalar cost computation with the same VPlan-based     │
│ cost computation used for vector VFs. This unifies the costing methodology,   │
│ making BestFactor selection consistent with vector VF evaluation and reducing │
│ disagreement with the legacy verification path.                               │
│ Concrete change:                                                              │
│ Original:                                                                     │
│   // TODO: Compute scalar cost using VPlan-based cost model.                  │
│   InstructionCost ScalarCost = CM.expectedCost(ScalarVF);                     │
│   LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "LV: Scalar loop costs: " << ScalarCost << ".\n");     │
│ Replacement:                                                                  │
│   // Compute scalar cost using the same VPlan-based cost model to keep        │
│ decisions consistent.                                                         │
│   VPlan &ScalarPlan = getPlanFor(ScalarVF);                                   │
│   InstructionCost ScalarCost = cost(ScalarPlan, ScalarVF);                    │
│   LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "LV: Scalar loop VPlan costs: " << ScalarCost <<       │
│ ".\n");                                                                       │
│ No further logic needs adjustment because subsequent code constructs          │
│ ScalarFactor from ScalarCost and proceeds identically.                        │
│ This preserves assertions and avoids modifying verification conditions.       │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ By switching the scalar VF cost computation in computeBestVF() to use the     │
│ same VPlan-based path as vector VFs, we eliminate asymmetric cost modeling    │
│ that was the source of the disagreement and assertion failure. This aligns    │
│ the selection logic, prevents spurious mismatches with the legacy model, and  │
│ honors the existing TODO. Expected effect: assertion no longer triggers for   │
│ the reproducer, and VF selection between the two models becomes stable unless │
│ there are genuine simplifications (in which case the existing fallback logic  │
│ applies).                                                                     │
