  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe assertion in
LoopVectorizationPlanner::computeBestVF() fires because the VF chosen by the new
VPlan-based cost model (BestFactor.Width) disagrees with the VF chosen by the
legacy cost model (LegacyVF.Width), and the fallback check
planContainsAdditionalSimplifications() returns false, meaning there are no extra
simplifications in the selected VPlan to justify the difference. In the provided
reproducer, the loop is extremely simple and likely not profitable to vectorize.
The legacy model picks a vector VF while the VPlan-based model picks scalar (or
vice versa), causing the assertion.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe crash happens
immediately inside computeBestVF(), before any IR transformation is performed.
This confirms the failure is confined to the cost-model selection logic. The
debug-only output was empty because the pass aborts during VF selection. The
assertion condition:\n  (BestFactor.Width == LegacyVF.Width ||
planContainsAdditionalSimplifications(...))\nindicates widths differ and
planContainsAdditionalSimplifications returned false. This means the discrepancy
is purely due to differing cost computations, not structural
simplifications.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nInside computeBestVF(), scalar cost
is computed using:\n  InstructionCost ScalarCost =
CM.expectedCost(ScalarVF);\nwhile vector VFs use the new unified VPlan-based cost
path:\n  InstructionCost Cost = cost(*P, VF);\nThis mixes two different cost
modeling strategies: scalar uses only the legacy cost model; vector uses the
hybrid precomputeCosts + Plan.cost. In contrast, selectVectorizationFactor()
(legacy verifier path) uses CM.expectedCost() uniformly for all VFs. Because the
new path compares vector costs (VPlan-based) against a scalar cost (legacy-only),
profitability decisions can diverge from those of the all-legacy path even in the
absence of additional simplifications. For very small loops (like the reproducer
with trivially constant computations) the mismatch is more pronounced: the scalar
cost may appear relatively worse or better compared to a differently scaled
vector cost, leading to different VF choices and triggering the assertion that
assumes consistency unless simplifications exist. The comment above this code
even has a TODO acknowledging scalar cost should also use the VPlan-based cost
model.\nThus the root cause is the inconsistent costing method for scalar VF=1
versus vector VFs in computeBestVF(), violating the assumption behind the
assertion.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nEdit lines 7336-7338 in
llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp.\nReplace the legacy-only scalar
cost computation with the same VPlan-based cost computation used for vector VFs.
This unifies the costing methodology, making BestFactor selection consistent with
vector VF evaluation and reducing disagreement with the legacy verification
path.\nConcrete change:\nOriginal:\n  // TODO: Compute scalar cost using
VPlan-based cost model.\n  InstructionCost ScalarCost =
CM.expectedCost(ScalarVF);\n  LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << \"LV: Scalar loop costs: \" <<
ScalarCost << \".\\n\");\nReplacement:\n  // Compute scalar cost using the same
VPlan-based cost model to keep decisions consistent.\n  VPlan &ScalarPlan =
getPlanFor(ScalarVF);\n  InstructionCost ScalarCost = cost(ScalarPlan,
ScalarVF);\n  LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << \"LV: Scalar loop VPlan costs: \" <<
ScalarCost << \".\\n\");\nNo further logic needs adjustment because subsequent
code constructs ScalarFactor from ScalarCost and proceeds identically.\nThis
preserves assertions and avoids modifying verification conditions.\n\n5.
Conclusion:\nBy switching the scalar VF cost computation in computeBestVF() to
use the same VPlan-based path as vector VFs, we eliminate asymmetric cost
modeling that was the source of the disagreement and assertion failure. This
aligns the selection logic, prevents spurious mismatches with the legacy model,
and honors the existing TODO. Expected effect: assertion no longer triggers for
the reproducer, and VF selection between the two models becomes stable unless
there are genuine simplifications (in which case the existing fallback logic
applies).",
